Audit Logging Using AOP (Clean Architecture)

Now we implement enterprise-grade audit logging without polluting business logic.

In banking/trading systems, audit logging is mandatory for compliance.

Examples of auditable events:

Money transfer

Account creation

Password change

Trade execution

Role modification

🧠 Why Use AOP for Audit?

Without AOP:

log.info("Audit: Money transfer started");
auditRepository.save(...);


Your service becomes messy.

With AOP:

✔ Business logic stays clean
✔ Audit logic centralized
✔ Reusable
✔ Easier to maintain
✔ Follows clean architecture principles

🏗 Final Architecture
Controller
   ↓
Service (@Audit)
   ↓
AuditAspect (AOP intercepts)
   ↓
Save AuditLog in DB

1️⃣ Step 1 – Create Audit Annotation
Audit.java
package com.bank.audit;

import java.lang.annotation.*;

@Target(ElementType.METHOD)
@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)
@Documented
public @interface Audit {
    String action();
}


This marks methods for auditing.

